    # [Scene: Marshlands | Dawn]

    scene bg ch13_f99e88_1 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The soft sluice of water through roots, a trowel scraping peat, distant gulls.]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A slow, rising acoustic motif—warm, patient.]
    "You are already damp with the morning—salt on the back of your neck, sketchbook thumb-smudged, lungs full of the raw, cold-sweet air that always pulls you taut with both grief and purpose. The meeting's choice from"
    "the Watchhouse still sits like a pebble in your palm: refuse the quick certainty of grand walls, return to the messy work of people and soil. You chose the soil."
    show jonah_reyes at left:
        zoom 0.7

    jonah_reyes "You look like you brought the Watchhouse home on your back."
    show elena_lena_maris at right:
        zoom 0.7

    elena_lena_maris "Maybe I did. It came with a lot of sticky notes."
    "He laughs; it warms the mist. Then he points to a cluster of volunteers—teenagers from the co-op, Rosie with a thermos, Dr. Asha checking a sensor. Momentum in small bodies, not a single, sweeping hand. It feels correct."
    show dr_asha_khatri at center:
        zoom 0.7

    dr_asha_khatri "Root them deep where the sediment holds. Not too close to last year's line—let the reeds do some of the work until the willows settle in."

    elena_lena_maris "And we stagger the plantings to prevent one storm from wiping us out. Monitor, adapt, share the data."

    dr_asha_khatri "Exactly. And make sure the apprentices know how to read each root. The marsh needs people who can listen as much as it needs engineers with specs."
    "You tuck a willow cutting into the mud and press—your fingers remembering, your knuckles scraping salt-stiffened scar tissue you still have near your brow. You think of the condemned house you grew up in, of Marco"
    "handing you a muddy wrench as if tools could stitch memory back together. That memory doesn't ache the way it used to; it's ballast now."

    menu:
        "Wade in barefoot—feel the tidal pull":
            "You strip off your boots, the cold finds the soles of your feet like a question. For a moment you hold still and let the mud take you. It grounds you, and when you stand the willows look smaller and the future feels less abstract."
        "Tape the boots tighter and stick to the plan":
            "You cinch your boots, clip the trowel to your belt, and return to the row with a steady, professional rhythm. Efficiency is a kind of care too; the seedlings will remember being placed with hands that knew what they were doing."

    # --- merge ---

    jonah_reyes "Barefoot can wait for later. We've got three hundred cuttings and two dozen volunteers who need dragging into rhythm."

    jonah_reyes "Barefoot can wait for later. We've got three hundred cuttings and two dozen volunteers who need dragging into rhythm."

    elena_lena_maris "Then let's drum the rhythm right."
    "The day stretches into a montage of small successes. You teach adolescents to knot sediment cages; Jonah shows a retired boatman how to splice geotextile into a simple silt fence. Rosie passes out sandwiches and more"
    "importantly, songs between instructions—old port shanties retuned with new verses about roots and rain. Marco arrives at noon, hair flattened under a cap, and for the first time in months his temper is softer, his jokes"
    "less defensive and more stitched with pride."
    hide jonah_reyes
    show marco_maris at left:
        zoom 0.7

    marco_maris "You always did like to make mud into a sculpture. I guess that's policy now."

    elena_lena_maris "If we're lucky, the sculpture keeps a house standing."

    marco_maris "Or at least keeps someone from having to night's-sleep in a shelter tent again."
    "The work hums like an instrument. There are moments of frustration—an irrigation line that kinks, a volunteer who quits after a bad night—but those are folded into hands that persist. The project calendar fills: training sessions,"
    "monitoring runs, a weekly open hour at the co-op where anyone can look at the data with a cup of Rosie’s coffee and ask questions."
    # [Scene: Rosie’s Co-op | Late Afternoon]
    hide elena_lena_maris
    hide dr_asha_khatri
    hide marco_maris

    scene bg ch13_f99e88_2 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Laughter, the clatter of cups, a guitar strummed in the corner.]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Upbeat folk rhythm—community cadence.]
    "Rosie is a hurricane of aprons and plans. Her co-op has become the informal operations center: supply drop-offs, volunteer sign-ups, and when funds run thin, ingenuity seeds new campaigns. You stand at the front desk with"
    "a stack of monitoring graphs and an awkward confidence that feels like new scaffolding for your voice."

    "Rosie" "Alright, Lenny—' (she uses the nickname like a spoon stirring warmth) '—people need to hear not just numbers but stories. Can you tell them what the marsh looked like before we planted, what it looks like now?"
    show elena_lena_maris at left:
        zoom 0.7

    elena_lena_maris "I can. But I want Jonah to show them the hands that do the work. People trust hands."
    show jonah_reyes at right:
        zoom 0.7

    jonah_reyes "I was hoping you'd say that. I can mimic a hand that sings."

    elena_lena_maris "Promise to keep the singing to a minimum during the funding pitch."

    jonah_reyes "No promises. Rosie insists on music."

    "Rosie" "It sells stew faster."
    "You and Jonah rehearse the pitch: technical details softened by human scale—how much sediment we've captured, how many households saw their basement water drop after the silt fences, how apprenticeships teach not only technique but also"
    "livelihoods. Dialogue ricochets back and forth until it feels like a duet, the two of you trading facts and faces until the narrative is both true and persuasive."

    menu:
        "Take the stage at the fundraiser and lead the pitch":
            "You step up when the room quiets. Your voice finds a steady line between technical confidence and personal story—people lean in. By the end there are more pledges than you'd hoped."
        "Play the guitar with Jonah and let Rosie lead the pitch":
            "You pick up the guitar, add a low harmony to Jonah and Rosie's chorus, and watch chairs fill with softer faces. The money comes in anyway—people give to what feels like a whole, living thing."

    # --- merge ---

    "Rosie" "You did both. You told the story and then you sang the last line with Jonah. It was all of it—heart and math. You should've seen the pledges."

    "Rosie" "You did both. You told the story and then you sang the last line with Jonah. It was all of it—heart and math. You should've seen the pledges."

    elena_lena_maris "We need all of it."

    jonah_reyes "And we needed you to tell them about anti-displacement clauses. That rattled some cages, but folks appreciated it."

    "Rosie" "Good. Keep rattling. Keeps the mice out."
    "The fundraiser brings short-term breath: funds for tools, one more portable sensor, a stipend to pay apprentices a modest wage. It's a patchwork of victory, but it stitches something visible into the town's fabric—people see their labor valued not as charity but as infrastructure."
    # [Scene: Boardwalk | Early Evening — Months Later]
    hide elena_lena_maris
    hide jonah_reyes

    scene bg ch13_f99e88_3 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: A crowd murmuring; children squealing as they chase after glow-strings; Rosie strumming a chorus.]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: The motif returns—richer now, layered with local voices and instruments.]
    "You walk the boardwalk with Jonah at your side. The marsh you helped braid is more confident—silt has gathered, willows stand at attention, and the sensor buoys blink their small green eyes at the bay. You're"
    "not under any illusion that the sea has bowed to your will. The work is slow, sometimes unglamorous, but it keeps things rooted."
    "A small group of apprentices demonstrate how to read tide lines and calibrate monitoring rigs. One of them—bookish, quick-fingered—looks at you with the steady resolve that makes you think of Marco when he was fifteen, sardonic and stubborn and then softened by purpose."

    "Apprentice" "We reduced sediment slippage by sixteen percent after rearranging the silt traps like you taught us."
    show elena_lena_maris at left:
        zoom 0.7

    elena_lena_maris "Then keep that sixteen percent and make it thirty-six."
    show jonah_reyes at right:
        zoom 0.7

    jonah_reyes "And I'll make sure you have the tools."
    "You exchange a look with Jonah—longer than a sentence, an accumulation of shared days and dirty hands and small, recurrent joys. You think of the decision you made months ago; it has become a horizon you walk toward every day."
    "Dr. Asha Khatri joins you, breathless from a last-minute review of data before the showcase. She slips an arm around your shoulder, the way mentors do when pride is too big for words."
    show dr_asha_khatri at center:
        zoom 0.7

    dr_asha_khatri "They'll keep measuring. They'll keep telling the story. You built something that will outlast a lot of speeches."

    elena_lena_maris "We built people who can tell the story."

    dr_asha_khatri "Exactly. That's resilience."
    "At the edge of the crowd, a polished presence steps forward—someone who could have been a discordant note in another life. Iris Valence stands a little outside the lantern glow, her trench open to the evening"
    "and her tablet tucked like a talisman to her chest. She watches the apprentices as if cataloguing the scene, then approaches, her expression complex—professional veneer threaded with something softer that might be, for you, an old"
    "habit to misread."
    hide elena_lena_maris
    show iris_valence at left:
        zoom 0.7

    iris_valence "The showcase is... impressive."
    hide jonah_reyes
    show elena_lena_maris at right:
        zoom 0.7

    elena_lena_maris "It is. The apprentices did the work."

    iris_valence "I came because the apprenticeship program is what I should have asked for at the start. I was impatient before—I thought scale alone could buy time. I misread the town. I want to offer funding for a sustained apprenticeship endowment—no strings beyond reporting and transparency."
    "Your heart does an unhelpful flutter—old histories press in—but you keep your face plain. The room is busy with music; it provides cover to parse the gesture."

    elena_lena_maris "What does 'no strings' mean to you? Valence Urbanworks doesn't do things without terms."

    iris_valence "I'm not trying to whitewash a past where my firm pushed a single answer. This is small. It will be audited and transparent. The money will be disbursed to the co-op and overseen by a committee that includes community seats. I want a hand in making amends, not a headline."

    elena_lena_maris "Community oversight. Clear reporting. Apprentices hired first when projects come in. You accept those as conditions?"

    iris_valence "Yes. And if you want me to put the funds into a trust managed by Dr. Asha and Rosie, I won't interfere. I want to fund things that hold people here—not move them."
    hide dr_asha_khatri
    show jonah_reyes at center:
        zoom 0.7

    jonah_reyes "That would make a difference. The apprenticeships mean jobs, yes, but also knowledge that doesn't walk away with a contractor."

    iris_valence "I know what you think of me. I don't expect immediate forgiveness. I expect action to be judged over years."
    "Elena 'Lena' Maris [thinking]: The past isn't erased by money or words. But a small, accountable investment in people—if it's done on your terms—could be a repair big enough to matter. It won't fix everything. It"
    "won't clean the memory of other choices. But it's a rope thrown where hands are willing to take it."

    elena_lena_maris "We'll draft the oversight terms. We want transparency and community governance. If Valence signs that, we'll accept the funding."

    iris_valence "Then I'll sign."
    "Her acceptance is not a clean reconciliation; it's a complex, pragmatic step. You let it be what it is: a bridging of resources to local stewardship. The apprentices gather near Rosie’s guitar while a child in"
    "a salt-stained jacket climbs the boardwalk railing to better see the marsh. A woman in the crowd starts clapping; others join. The music swells not because problems are solved, but because people are together and making,"
    "again, a thing that matters."

    elena_lena_maris "This is the slow repair."

    jonah_reyes "Mud, music, and work. The three pillars."
    "You laugh—it's light and certain. You realize you are no longer measuring victory against a single storm but against days like this: when people trade skills, when money is sober and overseen, when the town's culture is taught to a new generation."
    hide iris_valence
    hide elena_lena_maris
    hide jonah_reyes

    scene bg ch13_f99e88_4 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Rosie finishes a song. The crowd cheers. A gull calls far off.]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: The rising motif resolves into a warm, sustained chord—hopeful, not triumphant.]
    "You stand shoulder to shoulder with Jonah as the music carries across the water. His hand finds yours—callused, warm, familiar. You don't need grand promises from the sea. You need daily promises kept: training sessions, monitoring"
    "logs filed, community meetings where questions are asked aloud. You have chosen the slow work because it keeps people and place together."
    "Marco comes up behind you and claps you both on the shoulders. 'You two look good in mud,' he says, grinning."
    show elena_lena_maris at left:
        zoom 0.7

    elena_lena_maris "We do our best."
    show marco_maris at right:
        zoom 0.7

    marco_maris "You're doing more than that. You're making the town trust itself again."

    elena_lena_maris "That's the point."
    "Night folds around you like a blanket mended from many scraps. The apprenticeship funds sit on a future table, but they're real—an accountable offer that will pay wages and buy tools and, importantly, teach people to"
    "read the land and fight for their own rights to stay. Iris's presence at the edge is a reminder that repair often requires those who once tore to now help stitch. That doesn't absolve or erase"
    "history, but it can redirect it."
    "You think of the wall you refused, of the pilot that failed and taught you what it needed to teach, of the small, stubborn human arrangements that now look less fragile than they once did."

    elena_lena_maris "Would you stay, if things shift more—if funding dries, if storms get worse?"
    show jonah_reyes at center:
        zoom 0.7

    jonah_reyes "I stay unless leaving is the only way to keep people safe. But I don't think it's the only way yet. Not while this—' (he taps the mud-packed sole of his boot) '—this is alive."

    elena_lena_maris "Then we'll keep tending."
    "You let the music settle into your bones. The town has no neat ending in the face of a rising sea, but tonight is an ending of a kind: the end of a phase where you"
    "wondered whether scale had to mean erasure. Instead you have a growing web—apprentices who will teach their children, a co-op that signs grants with teeth, and a watchful community that counts both sediment and story."
    hide elena_lena_maris
    hide marco_maris
    hide jonah_reyes

    scene bg ch13_f99e88_5 at full_bg
